sect2.para:
According to the common factors approach, psychotherapy is a socially constructed and mediated healing practice (Laska et al.,
            2014
         ). It follows that the relationship between the clinician and client, called the therapeutic alliance, is the most highly researched and perhaps most critical common factor. The therapeutic alliance is characterized by an emotionally charged bond between the therapist and the client and a mutual agreement about the goals and tasks of psychotherapy (Laska et al., 
            2014
         ). Establishing a positive working alliance is easier said than done, but establishing a bond with the client is an important requisite for effective interviewing and ongoing psychotherapy
            psychotherapy
         , so it should be at the top of your priority list. Indeed, research has consistently identified that cultivation of a positive therapeutic relationship is essential to the success experienced by most clients (see thorough review by Norcross & Lambert, 
            2019
         ).

A similar skill to demonstrating empathy, and one that is arguably just as valuable in psychotherapy, is the psychotherapist’s ability to act in an accepting and affirming manner with their clients. Being kind and caring toward clients not only acts as positive reinforcement for their participation in treatment but also affirms their sense of worth (Farber & Doolin,
            2011
         ). Therapists can convey positive regard for their clients by commending them for attending their appointments and reaching goals or milestones, such as disclosing sensitive information that may have been difficult for the client to talk about. Demonstrating positive regard toward clients facilitates their innate tendency to grow and fulfill their capacity as human beings (Farber & Doolin, 
            2011
         ).
